### Current behavior

I have a function in my proto-file which returns a stream of data. The code is identical to the GRPC-sample in the NestJS repository (04-grpc): https://github.com/nestjs/nest/tree/master/sample/04-grpc
```
service HeroesService {
  rpc FindOne (HeroById) returns (Hero);
  rpc FindMany (stream HeroById) returns (stream Hero);
}
```

When I generate the TypeScript code for this, it sets the return-type to `Observable<HelloResponse>`, which is correct.

```
    export interface HeroesService {
        findOne(
            data: HeroById,
            metadata?: Metadata,
            ...rest: any[]
        ): Observable<Hero>;
        findMany(
            data: Observable<HeroById>,
            metadata?: Metadata,
            ...rest: any[]
        ): Observable<Hero>;
    }
```

Inside my NestJS controller I then implement this method using the decorator `@GrpcStreamMethod` like the following:

```
  @GrpcStreamMethod('HeroesService')
  findMany(data$: Observable<HeroById>): Observable<Hero> {
    const hero$ = new Subject<Hero>();

    const onNext = (heroById: HeroById) => {
      const item = this.items.find(({ id }) => id === heroById.id);
      hero$.next(item);
    };
    const onComplete = () => hero$.complete();
    data$.subscribe({
      next: onNext,
      complete: onComplete,
    });

    return hero$.asObservable();
  }
```

Calling this GRPC-method via an GRPC-client works fine. However, if I want to call the method directly inside my NestJS-app (e.g. within a unit-test), I have issues. The reason for this is that even though the method marked to return an Observable, and TypeScript shows no issues, actually calling the method returns a `Promise<Observable<...>>`, due to some handling in the decorator.

To have it work correctly with TypeScript, I therefore have to rewrite the implementation like this:

```
  @GrpcStreamMethod('HeroesService')
  async findMany(data$: Observable<HeroById>): Promise<Observable<Hero>> {
    const hero$ = new Subject<Hero>();

    const onNext = (heroById: HeroById) => {
      const item = this.items.find(({ id }) => id === heroById.id);
      hero$.next(item);
    };
    const onComplete = () => hero$.complete();
    data$.subscribe({
      next: onNext,
      complete: onComplete,
    });

    return hero$.asObservable();
  }
```

As this however doesn't match the class generated by the proto-file, I can no longer use it as an interface for my service to ensure type-safety (`class HeroController implements HeroesService`). If I keep the implementation as it should be, I can rely on type-safety, but have to do some shady code in the tests to correctly call the method.

### Minimum reproduction code

https://github.com/KingScouter/nestjs_grpcstreammethod_bug/tree/main/04-grpc

### Steps to reproduce

1. `npm i`
2. `npm run test`

### Expected behavior

The expected behavior would be that the method returns an Observable, as per declaration in TypeScript and in the generated code by ts-proto.

### NestJS version

11.1.9

